ederal government—until American settlers arrived. Congress abrogated treaties that it had promised would last “as long as the waters run,” and within a generation, the tribes were systematically stripped of their holdings, and were rescued from starvation only through public charity. Called a “work of art” by writer Oliver La Farge, And Still the Waters Run was so controversial when it was first published that Angie Debo was banned from teaching in Oklahoma for many years. Now with an incisive foreword by Amanda Cobb-Greetham, here is the acclaimed book that first documented the scandalous founding of Oklahoma on native land.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFive Civilized TribesxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazUnited StatesxGovernment relations. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  aAccountability.  aAdvocacy.  aAndrew Jackson.  aAngie Debo.  aAttempt.  aAunt.  aBill Anoatubby.  aBiosecurity.  aBlood quantum laws.  aBorder.  aBury My Heart at Wounded Knee.  aCess.  aCherokee Nation.  aCherokee.  aChickasaw Nation.  aChoctaw Nation of Oklahoma.  aCitizenship.  aCivilization.  aClassic book.  aCommunity leader.  aConcluding.  aConstitution.  aCorrespondent.  aCross-border cooperation.  aCultural heritage.  aCurator.  aDawes Commission.  aDetermination.  aDoctorate.  aDowry.  aEffectiveness.  aFederal law.  aFive Civilized Tribes.  aForeword.  aFrederick Jackson Turner.  aFunding opportunity announcement.  aFunding.  aGary Batton.  aGlobal governance.  aGovernance.  aGrant writing.  aHoward Zinn.  aIdeology.  aImperialism.  aIn This World.  aIndian Territory.  aIndian country.  aIndigenous peoples.  aInferiority complex.  aJames Fenimore Cooper.  aJurisdiction.  aLiterature.  aLynn Riggs.  